Newly appointed Home Affairs Minister Prof Hlengiwe Mkhize is looking beyond the criticism hurled at President Jacob Zuma over Friday s Cabinet reshuffle.She has vowed to serve with humility, respect and dignity . I want to be the best for the people, not for myself, but for this country, Mkhize said.Mkhize, who replaced Malusi Gigaba, will meet the new finance minister for a hand-over brief today. Everyone wants a secure, stable society and there are things I m looking at which, if I can strengthen, will make many people satisfied and experience being a South African or being on South African territory in a positive way, Mkhize said.She stressed the importance of processing people s entry into the country. We need to know who is where, doing what and punish those who prefer to operate illegally. She added it was key to properly and timeously process papers for those wanting to work and live in South Africa. We have to bring the compassion, ubuntu and humane aspects when we see genuine people wanting to live in our land, Mkhize said.She has served under South Africa s past presidents, Nelson Mandela, Thabo Mbeki, aswell as Zuma in different capacities.During Mandela s tenure as president, she was a commissioner at the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, doubling up as chairperson of the Reparations and Rehabilitation Committee.Betwen 2005 and 2008, she was the country s ambassador to the Netherlands and also served as vice-president of the member states of the International Criminal Court at The Hague during the same period.She served as deputy minister of correctional services (2009-2010), higher education (2010-2012) and economic development (2012-2014).As deputy minister of telecommunications and postal services, thousands of rural schools benefited from broadband.MTHOKOZISI DUBEmtokozisid@thenewage.co.za